Minor issue with indentation (minor because it's the first time I've had a need to do this in 23 years!):

```cs
    public class IndentingClass
    {
        private enum State { A, B, C };

        public void InconsistentIndenting(bool condition, State state)
        {
            // If an "if" statement is on the same line as a preceding "else", the indentation matches the "else" (as expected)
            if (state == State.A)
            {
            }
            else if (state == State.B)
            {
            }

            // However, other statements on the same line as an else (such as "switch") don't receive the same treatment and get extra indentation
            if (condition)
            {
            }
            else switch (state)
                {
                    case State.A:
                        break;
                    case State.B:
                        break;
                }
        }
    }
```

The obvious workarounds are to drop the switch to the next line, or surround it with braces, but despite it being an unusual construct, and though some may not consider it the best style, the treatment of "else switch" seems inconsistent with the treatment of "else if" (which is obviously a very common construct). 

The same is also seems to be true of other statements ("else while", "else do", "else try", etc) and although I've never come across a good reason to use those without surrounding braces, I think that given the language allows a single statement to follow an "else", it makes sense that they should be indented consistently.


