**Steps to Reproduce**:

Compile the following code:
```cs
#nullable enable
using System.Runtime.CompilerServices;

partial class C
{
  public string? Method1<T>(T arg) => null;
}

static class Program
{
  public static void Main()
  {
    var c = new C();
    string? x = null;

    c.Method1(x);
  }
}

partial class C
{
  [InterceptsLocation("Program.cs", 16, 7)]
  public string? Interceptor1<T>(T arg) where T: notnull => arg.ToString();
}

namespace System.Runtime.CompilerServices
{
  [AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Method, AllowMultiple = true)]
  public class InterceptsLocationAttribute : Attribute
  {
    public InterceptsLocationAttribute(string path, int line, int character) { }
  }
}
```

**Expected Behavior**:
A warning is reported for the intercepted call `c.Method1(x)` which is translated into `C.Interceptor1<string?>(x);` because the type argument doesn't satisfy the `where T: notnull` constraint on the interceptor method

**Actual Behavior**:
No warnings at all. The code crashes at runtime with a `NullReferenceException`

Here's a small example:

```cs
// before
class C
{
    int x = false; // error: no conversion from bool to int
}

// after
class C
{
    bool x = false;
}
```

In some cases, especially when a field's type is complex, it's easier to just use a bogus type for the field, and run a fixer which changes the field's type to match its initializer.

It's not uncommon to rely on this kind of workflow when working with older versions of Java, e.g. just give everything type 'int' and use an auto-fixer to replace that with the actual type. In C# we use `var` for this when it comes to locals, but of course not every variable is a local.

Here's a screenshot of when I would have liked to have this:

![image](https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/assets/5833655/c6ff569d-e174-46ca-b49e-23d4b5327a16)

since it could have filled in `KeyValuePair<string, ReportDiagnostic>` for me.

note that a feature like this would have to be thoughtfully designed with respect to existing usages of the variable. It's possible the best thing would be to just offer to change the type at each assignment where a conversion error is present, even if this would cause an error elsewhere in the compilation. After all, this would essentially be a refactoring tool and user is affirming their intent to change the type of the variable.
